Title: The State of Workers' Mental Health Perceptions in the Tech Industry¶

Problem¶

This data exploration will address the problem of society's worsening mental health in the context of workers in the technology industry. Worldwide, mental health is a health problem to indiviudals. One's health and perception of their health may affect their job performance. With a field as highly demanding as the tech industry, the state of workers' mental health and perceptions deserves investigation.

Background¶

10% of the global burden of disease is attributed to neuropsychiatric disorders. The leading contributors to years lived with disability are mental, neurological, and substance use disorders (Global Mental Health, APA). More locally, mental health in the United States continues to pose threats to people's wellbeing. Among adults, the prevalance of mental illness is increasing, suicidal ideation is increasing, and treatment is inaccessible (Mental Health America). These statistics prove that we need to pay attention to mental health in our communities.

Reports have found that the tech industry's workplace culture tends to be less supportive of marginalized communities, including women (Washington State Labor Education and Research Center and SEIU) and people of color (Anil Dash). In the summer of 2014, many notable tech companies including Google, Yahoo, and Facebook reported remarkably low statistics regarding a diverse staff and committed to do better. According to their Diversity Annual Report, as of 2020, Google's employees were 68% male and 54% white (Google). Have these companies really delivered on their promises?

Krieger et al. found that class, race, and gender inequities in the healthcare workplace lead to risk of socially hazardous experiences (International Journal of Health Services). Do these findings transcend the type of workplace? Socially isolating experiences can affect workers' mental health (Journal of Interpersonal Violence). How do these experiences affect workers specifically in the tech industry?

Mental Health America explored how company culture can impact employees' mental health. Emphasis was placed on the value of open and safe communication as well as a communicative managerial style. However, nsiders have reported that the tech industry upholds unhealthy workforce habits (Wharton UPenn). Among tech workers in China, controversy has risen regarding '996' culture. '996' culture is the expectation of Chinese workers from some tech companies to work from 9am to 9pm six days a week (NY Times). How do these industry standards affect workers' mental health?

Data Source¶

I will be analyzing the SMI Mental Health in Tech Survey 2016 dataset. In 2016, this survey was offered to workers worldwide in the tech industry. Questions include demographics such as age, gender, location, as well as treatment of mental health in the industry such as employers' discussion of mental health benefits, participants' comfort of disclosing about mental health conditions, and any mental health conditions participants felt comfortable sharing.

Research Questions¶

These research questions aim to narrow down the answer to general question of what factors affect mental health perceptions and conditions in the tech industry?

  1. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by country?

    Given the global issue of mental health discussed earlier, mental health is persistent among cultures. The World Health Organization is increasing investment to mental health resources (WHO). It is interesting to wonder if culture affects the perception of mental health. By analyzing survey responses based on participants' locations, I can investigate cultural differences. Findings may suggest different needs for mental health resources based on the state of mental health in different cultures. Findings may also lead to investigations into different countries' workplace cultures to understand adaptive and maladaptive aspects of the industry.

  2. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by gender?

    As discussed earlier, women tend to have different experiences than men in the tech workforce. Is there a correlation between gender and how workers experience conditions around mental health in their employment? Results may suggest the importance of challenging normal gender dynamics or changing how gender dynamics are currently treated in industry.

  3. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by age/generation?

    Research suggests that members of different generations identify and conceptualize mental health and mental illness differently (APA) (Avera, Georgia Southern University). It is common for concepts to evolve from generation to generation. Analyzing responses based on age may provide insight into points of contention among workers, or between workers and employers.

  4. Overall, how do workers perceive mental health in the workforce?

    Converse to the first three research questions investigating subpopulations, this question hopes to understand any general trends of perceptions of mental health in the workforce. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ at all based on aspects of their identities, or are there any shared values among all workers?

The p=value of the Shapiro-Wilk test performed on the ages of participants is 6.182674246822375e-20.

According to the Shapiro-Wilk test that tests for normality, the p-value of age distribution is 6.18 * 10-20, which is less than the chosen alpha level of 0.05. Thus the null hypothesis that the data is normally distributed is rejected.

Based on the distribution of the data, the data is overly representative of young, American men. This will be acknowledged further in the ethical concerns.

Data analysis¶

The following survey question results will be analyzed to answer the 3 reserach questions:

  • Would you feel comfortable discussing a mental health disorder with your coworkers?

  • Would you feel comfortable discussing a mental health disorder with your direct supervisor(s)?

  • Would you be willing to bring up a physical health issue with a potential employer in an interview?

  • Would you bring up a mental health issue with a potential employer in an interview?

  • Do you feel that being identified as a person with a mental health issue would hurt your career?

  • Do you think that team members/co-workers would view you more negatively if they knew you suffered from a mental health issue?

Run Chi-Square tests for Independence on question results based on subpopulations of gender, country of residence, and generation.

In [75]:
headers = ['DiscussMHCowrk', 'DiscussMHSuper', 'PHInterview', 
           'MHInterview', 'MHIHurtCareer', 'CwrkNegViewYouMH']
gender_pvalues = []
country_pvalues = []
age_pvalues = []
for header in headers:
    gender = pd.crosstab(base.Gender, base[header]).values.tolist()
    gender_stat = st.chi2_contingency(gender)
    gender_pvalues.append(gender_stat[1])
    
    country = pd.crosstab(base.Country, base[header]).values.tolist()
    country_stat = st.chi2_contingency(country)
    country_pvalues.append(country_stat[1])

    age = base.groupby(pd.cut(base.Age, age_range))[header]
    temp_age_array = []
    temp_age_arr = 0
    temp_first_arr = 0
    index = 0 
    age_list = []
    for name, group in age:
        to_add = group.value_counts().sort_index().tolist()
        if (header == 'CwrkNegViewYouMH'):
            index += 1 
        if (index == 3):
            to_add.insert(2, 0)
        age_list.append(to_add)
    age_data = (np.array(age_list, dtype=object))
    age_stat = st.chi2_contingency(age_data)
    age_pvalues.append(age_stat[1])

Results¶

Mainly Chi-Square Test of Independence were conducted on this data because it compares the relationship between categorical variables and this data is categorical. These tests are run with a significance level of 0.05. The null hypothesis of these tests is that there is no relationship between the variables being compared. If a test result's p-value is less than my significance level of 0.05, I reject the null hypothesis and conclude that a relationship exists between the variables.

Revisiting Research Questions¶

The research questions I set out to answer with this data were:

  1. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by country?

  2. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by gender?

  3. Do workers' perceptions of mental health differ by age/generation?

  4. Overall, how do workers perceive mental health in the workforce?

First I will address research question 2. In a few instances, there was a significant difference between survey question results based on the genders of the participants. From these results, I can suggest that more often than men, women think or know that having a mental health condition would hurt their career or negatively affect how their co-workers view them. Additionally, women are less likely than men to disclose either a physical or mental health condition during a job interview.

To address questions 1 and 3, this data suggests workers' perceptions of mental health generally do not differ by country or generation. Based on the statistical tests performed, there was not significant difference based on workers' country of residence of generation with which they belong to with one exception. I will first address this exception.

Results differed based on generation when asked if participants would disclose mental or physical health conditions during a job interview. Regarding generation, participants of the Boomer generation were overwhelmingly least likely to disclose any health condition compared to participants of the Generation X or Millenial Generation.

Results to these questions also technically differed based on country of residence. The difference in this data was that participants from the Netherlands greatly answered "Maybe" (instead of "Yes" or "No") to the question "Would you bring up a mental health issue with a potential employer in an interview?". Although these results suggest some hesitation or uncertainty among participants from the Netherlands, not many substantial questions can be drawn from these results.

Overall, there was no significant difference to results based on country of residence or generation. This leads into the answer to research question 4, regarding the overall trends of workers' perceptions of mental health in the workforce. For questions with no significant difference between identifiers and results, results could be analyzed altogether. This analysis yields results that participants are split in thirds ("Maybe", "No", "Yes") about if they would feel comfortable discussing a mental health condition with either their co-workers or direct supervisors. These mixed results may suggest other confounding variables among participants that affect their comfort discussing mental health conditions.

Another trend that occured in the results was that overall, all participants were more likely to bring up a physical health condition than a mental health condition in a job interview. This suggests that among workers, physical health conditions are perceived to be more normal or acceptable in the workforce than mental health conditions.

Overall, there are trends that suggest discomfort or possible stigma around mental health in the tech workplace. This suggests the need for further intervention to improve workers' perception, and more importantly, treatment of mental health. This responsibility falls on the tech industry employers. As they improve the treatment of mental health in their workplaces, such as insurance benefits and workforce habits that are conducive to stable mental health, workers' perceptions will be affected by these observable and meaningful changes.

Limitations and Concluding Ethical Concerns¶

As discussed in the analysis and visuals of participant demographics, the participants majorly consist of Millenial, American men. An ethical concern here is the lack of representation of participants of other identities. Even when analyzed by different demographics, this data may overrepresent the opinions of Millenial, American men. Furthermore, these demographics are reflective of an even larger problem: the underrepresented communities in the tech industry. As analysis of workers in the tech industry, I acknowledge the heterogeneous culture of the tech industry that favors white men. Although this data is representative of this bias, I do not support or aim to perpetuate the current unfair workforce demographics.

Another limitation of this data is the handling of participants' gender in data cleaning. This survey collected gender dynamics with a fill-in-the-blank question. The responses included some participants identifying beyond the gender binary of male and female. However, there were not enough gender diverse participants to significantly offer any statistical conclusions. As a result, this data only considers male and female participants when analyzing responses based on gender. This is a dangerous limitiation that overlooks many people's gender identities. This limitation may be resolved in future work with more aware and intentional collection of data. Furthermore, this limitation acknowledges the need for more representation for and fair treatment towards gender diverse people working in the tech industry.

Mental health is a sensitive topic to approach. An ethical concern is that analyzing people's mental health in the context of their work may minimize their value as individuals, perpetuating the harmful conflation of people as workers. Many of the countries represented in this survey data are capitalist, and I consider this factor worth the risk of the acknowledged ethical concern. Capitalism does not seem to be going anywhere, and analyzing the experience of people in the workforce may offer insight into supporting their experience and challenging barriers of the existing system. Regardless, in my reporting of the data I will be intentional in honoring that these perspectives come from individuals with jobs in the tech industry who maintain livelihoods beyond their work that may have affected their responses.

Another ethical concern regarding the sensitive nature of mental health is its treatment in the workplace. The data includes questions regarding the discussion of mental health in the workplace from employers. Althought employers discussing mental health and mental health benefits is generally seen as a good thing, discussing the topic may be upsetting to people in the work setting. This topic must be approached with sensitivity.
